      "content": "Taking ibuprofen every 2 hours, even at the lowest recommended dosage, can still pose risks due to the accumulation of the drug in your system, potentially reaching toxic levels over time, especially if you have underlying health issues or are elderly. The American Pain Society suggests a maximum daily limit of 3200mg for adults to minimize potential side effects.\n\nIf you're determined to use over-the-counter medications without consulting a doctor, consider taking the lowest effective dose that brings relief, spaced out more than every 2 hours. For example, after waking, you could take a 400mg dose every 4 to 6 hours. This strategy allows for consistent pain relief while reducing overall milligram intake and minimizing the risk of overdose:\n\n- Dose 1: 400mg at 0800\n- Dose 2: 400mg at 1240\n- Dose 3: 400mg at 1800\n- Add another dose of 400mg if needed in the evening (for example, 2000 hours)\n\nWith any medication, it's essential to be mindful of the maximum daily limit, recommended intervals, and signs of adverse effects. If you experience any concerning symptoms or if your pain doesn't subside with conservative measures, it's advisable to",
